WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.880
And Scott, if you could
please introduce yourself

00:00:02.880 --> 00:00:04.770
by telling us where you go to school

00:00:04.770 --> 00:00:05.970
and what grade you're in.

00:00:05.970 --> 00:00:08.940
I go to Glasgow Middle School
and I'm in seventh grade.

00:00:08.940 --> 00:00:12.270
Excellent. We are gonna
move on to the first question.

00:00:12.270 --> 00:00:15.000
What is the value of 255-
(buzzer beeps)

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:16.770
Scott?
5,000.

00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:19.350
5,000 is the correct answer.
(audience applauds)

00:00:19.350 --> 00:00:21.810
I grew up, like my whole life was math

00:00:21.810 --> 00:00:23.040
and programming competitions.
- Yeah.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:25.830
I was world champion of
competitive programming in 2014.

00:00:25.830 --> 00:00:27.990
And I remember talking about
this with some of my friends,

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:29.580
and do you guys think
there's ever gonna be a day

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:31.320
where AI can actually just do

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:33.060
all of these things that we do?

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:36.360
And to say the obvious, it's crazy.

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:38.923
Yeah.
(Scott laughs)

00:00:42.629 --> 00:00:45.869
What we do at Cognition
is we build Devin,

00:00:45.869 --> 00:00:47.339
the first AI software engineer

00:00:47.339 --> 00:00:49.949
and a suite of tools around that.

00:00:49.949 --> 00:00:52.559
We work with a lot of the biggest
institutions in the world.

00:00:52.559 --> 00:00:54.929
We work with banks, health insurers,

00:00:54.929 --> 00:00:56.972
governments, private equity firms.

00:00:57.505 --> 00:00:59.305
Our whole mission is
to help build software

00:00:59.305 --> 00:01:01.318
around the world 10 times faster.

00:01:03.839 --> 00:01:05.219
You sort of had a singular vision

00:01:05.219 --> 00:01:07.169
on what Devin was gonna look like.

00:01:07.169 --> 00:01:08.969
I'm curious like how you
managed to stick with it.

00:01:08.969 --> 00:01:11.909
We just care so much more
about the art and craft

00:01:11.909 --> 00:01:13.409
of software engineering on the ground,

00:01:13.409 --> 00:01:16.739
and how do we figure out how
to go and make that much faster

00:01:16.739 --> 00:01:19.019
and solve all the practical
problems and unblock that.

00:01:19.019 --> 00:01:21.659
It always felt like you had
a very collaborative attitude

00:01:21.659 --> 00:01:23.309
towards how to make this happen together.

00:01:23.309 --> 00:01:25.589
Very vividly remember my
first conversation with Daria.

00:01:25.589 --> 00:01:27.456
I got on the call with him,
I was talking about like,

00:01:27.456 --> 00:01:29.279
"Yeah, so we're working on this."

00:01:29.279 --> 00:01:30.353
He stopped me and he's like,

00:01:30.353 --> 00:01:32.039
"Don't worry, you don't
have to pitch me on this,

00:01:32.039 --> 00:01:33.899
the concept, I totally get it."

00:01:33.899 --> 00:01:35.249
We were doing something
that people didn't really

00:01:35.249 --> 00:01:36.386
believe was possible-
- Yeah, yeah.

00:01:36.386 --> 00:01:38.819
And I appreciated that a
lot from the very beginning.

00:01:38.819 --> 00:01:41.309
We've also started launching
some of our own products,

00:01:41.309 --> 00:01:42.209
like Claude Code.

00:01:42.209 --> 00:01:43.379
As our relationships evolved,

00:01:43.379 --> 00:01:45.059
I'm curious what your
feelings are about it.

00:01:45.059 --> 00:01:46.349
I really appreciate that you guys

00:01:46.349 --> 00:01:47.669
have been really transparent with us.

00:01:47.669 --> 00:01:50.969
I've always thought about it
as I really just don't think

00:01:50.969 --> 00:01:53.339
there's gonna be a single
product that does all of code

00:01:53.339 --> 00:01:54.599
and all of software engineering.

00:01:54.599 --> 00:01:56.759
There are so many experiences to serve.

00:01:56.759 --> 00:01:58.529
And I think from that
perspective, there's so much more

00:01:58.529 --> 00:02:00.449
for us to do together
than there is separate,

00:02:00.449 --> 00:02:01.829
and that's what we're excited about.

00:02:01.829 --> 00:02:03.869
Yeah.
(subdued music)

00:02:03.869 --> 00:02:05.669
From the beginning, I always loved

00:02:05.669 --> 00:02:07.229
that you could take any idea that you had

00:02:07.229 --> 00:02:08.939
and turn it into reality.

00:02:08.939 --> 00:02:11.849
Everyone will be able to turn
those ideas into reality.

00:02:11.849 --> 00:02:13.653
We've been able to make
so much more progress

00:02:13.653 --> 00:02:16.769
and see companies build much, much faster

00:02:16.769 --> 00:02:18.329
than they have been before.

00:02:18.329 --> 00:02:19.889
By getting to work with Anthropic,

00:02:19.889 --> 00:02:22.409
we're able to go and deliver customers

00:02:22.409 --> 00:02:25.649
the exact capabilities
that they're looking for.

00:02:25.649 --> 00:02:27.269
We've been able to help bring folks

00:02:27.269 --> 00:02:29.939
to a new era of software engineering.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.430
This is a world where building
software is just as easy

00:02:32.430 --> 00:02:34.608
as telling your computer what to do.

00:02:34.608 --> 00:02:37.191
(gentle music)

